content: I photographed LeBron in the backyard of one of his two homes in Akron, Ohio. This picture is all about him—like a studio portrait but on location. LeBron is always good in front of the camera—strong in terms of physicality and energy.—Walter Iooss Jr., 2022
title: LeBron James, 2005

content: This photograph of Chloë Sevigny was taken while on assignment for i.D. Magazine in 1995. She had just been discovered by Larry Clark for his film “Kids.” As great a personality in person as she was in the film. We did the photoshoot at the home of a designer in the Lower East Side. She was really nice and sweet and was one of the sexiest subjects I have photographed to this day. —Cati Gonzalez, 2022
title: Chloë Sevigny, 1995

content: In 1976 I spent six weeks in Hanalei, Kauai, shooting a story on surfing, all shot from a helicopter. At one point, this surfer wiped out and lost his board, which floated in over the reef. So, my helicopter pilot, Red Johnson, tilted the helicopter and blew the board back out to him in the lineup. Sometimes we would drop in too low and accidentally blow surfers off the waves. There were no restrictions of any variety for helicopters in 1976. We were free as a bird. —Walter Iooss Jr., 2022
title: Tunnels Beach, 1976

content: Poster girl and supermodel for the waif generation, shooting with me for Allure Magazine in the early days. One of the coolest I've ever known. —Sante D'Orazio, 2022

content: I spent the 2001 season with The Lakers photographing their star athletes, like Shaq, Kobe, Rick Fox, and coach Phil Jackson. At this point, we had done so many pics, and they were like, “really, another one??” You can see Shaq and Kobe’s interest levels. It's the most perfect disinterested photo ever.—Walter Iooss Jr., 2022
title: Shaq & Kobe, 2001

content: I went to the first 54 consecutive Super Bowls until my streak ended in 2020 due to the pandemic. I took this picture during Superbowl XXXVI, which was the last time I photographed one from the field. I'm so close to Tom in this picture. I am probably on a 17mm fish-eye lens. Tom has won more Super Bowls than any other player in history, which is why he has recently “unretired.” Once you’ve retired, your best years as an athlete are over. He knows and wants another one. -Walter Iooss Jr., 2022
title: Tom Brady, 2002

content: Serena’s body, form, and strength give you a feeling of what she is—hands down, the most incredible women's tennis player of all time. This is the original picture, which was never seen until recently. —Walter Iooss Jr., 2022

content: I made this portrait in a vestibule of Michael's home in 1998. I was shooting on 4x5 sheet film. The big question is always why Michael is wearing a #5 earring—that is how many championships he and The Bulls had won at this point. Not long after this picture, they would win their sixth NBA Championship, Michael would retire, and management would dismantle the team. This is why they refer to their 1998 season as 'The Last Bull Run.' Everyone knew it was going to be over. —Walter Iooss Jr., 2022
title: Michael Jordan, 1998

title: Tyson Beckford, 1994

content: For this session, I had 7.5 minutes on the clock to photograph three different setups! When Tiger first arrived, we discussed the pictures, and I purposefully spoke slowly to him to slow the pace down on set. And, instead of showing my test shots, I showed him pictures from my S.I. Swimsuit shoots and his eyes lit up. That got his attention. I knew I had him. You have to make your subject enjoy themselves. Like everyone else, he’s human. Then we shot. -Walter Iooss Jr., 2022
title: Tiger Woods, 2007

content: Never a dull moment. Hates wearing clothes but always wears a smile. —Sante D'Orazio, 2022

content: I spent the 2001 season with The Lakers photographing their star athletes, like Shaq, Kobe, Rick Fox, and coach Phil Jackson. At this point, we had done so many pics, and they were like, “really, another one??” You can see Shaq and Kobe’s interest levels. It's the most perfect disinterested photo ever.—Walter Iooss Jr., 2022
title: Shaq & Kobe, 2001

content: I photographed LeBron in the backyard of one of his two homes in Akron, Ohio. This picture is all about him—like a studio portrait but on location. LeBron is always good in front of the camera—strong in terms of physicality and energy.—Walter Iooss Jr., 2022
title: LeBron James, 2005

content: I went to the first 54 consecutive Super Bowls until my streak ended in 2020 due to the pandemic. I took this picture during Superbowl XXXVI, which was the last time I photographed one from the field. I'm so close to Tom in this picture. I am probably on a 17mm fish-eye lens. Tom has won more Super Bowls than any other player in history, which is why he has recently “unretired.” Once you’ve retired, your best years as an athlete are over. He knows and wants another one. -Walter Iooss Jr., 2022
title: Tom Brady, 2002

content: I photographed Pharrell Williams for Trace Magazine in 2003 at an NYC recording studio while working on a song for Jay-Z’s album. There was a moment during the session when we went into another room where there was a piano, and he played the chords as he sang to me Catalina, Catalina... while insisting that I sing with him. It was definitely an authentic “happy” moment. —Cati Gonzalez, 2022
title: Pharrell Williams, 2003

content: I was shooting Gronk for a cover of Sports Illustrated during the pre-season. I was assigned to make some portraits, but Gronk had the best “spike,” so that is what I wanted to shoot. As soon as I showed him a test image, he loved it. —Walter Iooss Jr., 2022

content: For this session, I had 7.5 minutes on the clock to photograph three different setups! When Tiger first arrived, we discussed the pictures, and I purposefully spoke slowly to him to slow the pace down on set. And, instead of showing my test shots, I showed him pictures from my S.I. Swimsuit shoots and his eyes lit up. That got his attention. I knew I had him. You have to make your subject enjoy themselves. Like everyone else, he’s human. Then we shot. -Walter Iooss Jr., 2022
title: Tiger Woods, 2007

content: In 2006 I photographed the entire Manchester United team and their coaches on the giant 20x24” Polaroid camera for a book project. I was never really a soccer fan until recent years, and it’s embarrassing that I didn't know much about Christiano and all the players at that time. Now I love soccer, almost more than anything else! Christiano is like a god in this photo. He’s oozing with confidence. —Walter Iooss Jr., 2022
title: Cristiano Ronaldo, 2006

content: “The Wiz.” In 1996 I was doing a book with Griffey called “Junior: Griffey on Griffey.” I made this picture pre-game at Camden Yards. It looks like he's mid-action in a game, but it's all choreographed and artificially lit. I have always been fixated on walls and backgrounds, and I loved this advertisement. content: Serena’s body, form, and strength give you a feeling of what she is—hands down, the most incredible women's tennis player of all time. We’ve worked together many times, and she is so smart and always professional. This picture was a cover of Sports Illustrated, but because I shot it on black & white film, the magazine ended up colorizing the image and stripped out the background so they could lay text over it. This is the original picture, which was never seen until recently. —Walter Iooss Jr., 2022
